  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why do you find so many snakes at night compared to the amount of snakes found in the morning?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why you might encounter more snakes at night compared to the morning:\n\n1. **Temperature Regulation**: Snakes are ectothermic (cold-blooded), meaning they rely on external temperatures to regulate their body heat. During the day, especially in hot climates, snakes often seek shelter to avoid overheating. At night, the cooler temperatures are more favorable for them to become active and hunt.\n\n2. **Prey Activity**: Many of the prey species that snakes hunt, such as rodents and amphibians, are also more active at night. This nocturnal activity aligns with the snakes' hunting patterns, increasing the likelihood of encountering them during these hours.\n\n3. **Avoiding Predators**: Being active at night helps some snake species avoid diurnal predators, such as birds of prey. The cover of darkness provides an additional layer of safety for snakes to move around and forage.\n\n4. **Behavioral Adaptations**: Some snake species are naturally nocturnal, meaning they are adapted to be active during the night. This behavior increases their chances of being seen at night rather than during the day.\n\n5. **Human Activity**: During the day, human activity is typically higher, which can drive snakes into hiding. At night, with fewer people around, snakes may feel safer to venture out.\n\nThese factors combined contribute to the higher likelihood of encountering snakes during nighttime hours.",
